ECR
Amazon ECR (Elastic Container Registry) is a fully managed Docker image registry provided by AWS that securely stores, manages, and retrieves container images. 
It integrates seamlessly with ECS, EKS, Fargate, and CI/CD tools, allowing applications to pull images directly during deployment. 
ECR provides high availability, fast image delivery, IAM-based access control, encryption, and automated image cleanup using lifecycle policies.
It removes the need to manage your own registry servers, making it a secure and efficient place to store Docker images for production workloads.

ECS
Amazon ECS (Elastic Container Service) is a fully managed container orchestration service from AWS that lets you run, manage, and scale Docker containers.
ECS handles scheduling, scaling, and maintaining containerized applications across compute options like EC2 instances or AWS Fargate (serverless).
It integrates closely with other AWS services such as ECR, ALB, CloudWatch, and IAM, making it easy to deploy and operate container-based applications without needing to manage your own Kubernetes cluster.

EKS
Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service) is a fully managed Kubernetes service provided by AWS that makes it easy to run Kubernetes applications without having to install, operate, or maintain your own Kubernetes control plane. EKS automatically manages the Kubernetes masters, API servers, and etcd storage, ensuring high availability and security. You can run workloads on either Amazon EC2 instances or AWS Fargate. 
It integrates deeply with AWS services like IAM, VPC, CloudWatch, and ALB, giving you a scalable, reliable, and production-ready platform for deploying containerized applications using standard Kubernetes tools and configurations.


About Project

In this project, I created a Docker image for my static website and pushed it to Amazon
ECR.
Then I deployed the same image in two ways:
● EKS (Kubernetes) → using cluster, deployment, and service.
● ECS (Fargate & EC2) → using task definition and service.
Finally, I accessed the website using the Load Balancer DNS or Public IP.




Creating an ECR Repository and Pushing a Docker Image
This document explains how to create an Amazon ECR repository, build a Docker image, and push it to ECR.
1. Creating an ECR Repository
Steps
Navigate to Amazon ECR in the AWS Console.


Click Create repository.


Enter a repository name.


Click Create to finish.


If you are unsure about the Docker push commands, click View push commands inside the repository — AWS provides all required commands.
2. Preparing the Environment for Docker & ECR Push
You need a terminal that can authenticate to AWS.
If you are using your local machine/bash, configure AWS CLI (aws configure).


If you are using an EC2 instance, the instance needs proper IAM permissions.


3. Creating an IAM Role for EC2 (Required Only for EC2 Terminal,if you dont configure aws cli)
Steps
Go to IAM → Roles → Create role.


Under Trusted entity, choose AWS Service.


For Use case, select EC2, then click Next.


Attach the policy:


AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryFullAccess


Provide a role name and click Create role.


Now attach the role to your EC2 instance:


Stop the instance


Go to Actions → Security → Modify IAM role


Select the newly created role


Attach it


4. Installing Docker and Node.js on EC2
Connect to the EC2 terminal and run:
yum update -y
yum install git curl -y
yum install docker -y
systemctl start docker

Install Node.js
curl -fsSL https://rpm.nodesource.com/setup_22.x | sudo bash -
sudo yum install -y nodejs
5. Clone the Application Repository
git clone https://github.com/Yaswanthy23/DevOps-Project-Zomato-Kastro.git
cd <foldername>
A Dockerfile already exists in the cloned folder.
vi Dockerfile
# Use Node.js 16 slim as the base image
FROM node:16-slim
# Set the working directory
WORKDIR /app
# Copy package.json and package-lock.json to the working directory
COPY package*.json ./
# Install dependencies
RUN npm install
# Copy the rest of the application code
COPY . .
# Build the React app
RUN npm run build
# Expose port 3000 (or the port your app is configured to listen on)
EXPOSE 3000
# Start your Node.js server (assuming it serves the React app)  
CMD ["npm", "start"]
6. Build the Docker Image
docker build -t zomato .
7. Authenticate Docker to ECR
Run the command generated by AWS (or use the example below):
aws ecr get-login-password --region ap-south-1 \
| docker login --username AWS --password-stdin 643625512213.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com
8. Tag the Docker Image
docker tag zomato:latest 643625512213.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/zomato-image:latest
9. Push the Docker Image to ECR
docker push 643625512213.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/zomato-image:latest
Note
The exact commands for authentication, tagging, and pushing are also available in the “View push commands” section inside your ECR repository.


Deploying ECR image on Amazon ECS Using Fargate
1. Create ECS Cluster (Fargate)
Go to ECS → Clusters → Create Cluster
Enter cluster name:

zomato-cluster
Select AWS Fargate as the infrastructure.


Click Create.


2. Create Task Definition (Fargate)
Navigate to ECS → Task Definitions → Create New Task Definition


Launch type: Fargate
Enter task name:

 zomato-task
Configure OS, CPU, and memory (leave default unless needed).


Task Role: None


Execution Role: Default (AWS creates it automatically)


Container Definition
Container name: zomato


Image URI: ECR image URL (from the ECR repo you created earlier)


Port mapping:


Container port: 3000


Click Create.
3. Create ECS Service Using Fargate
Navigate to:

 ECS → Clusters → zomato-cluster → Create Service
Service Configuration
Launch type: FARGATE


Task definition: zomato-task


Service name: zomato-service


Number of tasks: 1


4. Load Balancer Settings (Created During Service Creation)
Enable Application Load Balancer


Create a new ALB:


Name: zomato-lb


Listener: HTTP : 80


Create a new Target Group:


Name: zomato-tg-3000


Target type: IP


Port: 3000 (because container runs on 3000)


Container to Route Traffic
Container name: zomato


Container port: 3000


5. Networking Configuration
Subnets: Public Subnets


Auto-assign Public IP: ENABLED


Security Group:


Allow inbound 3000 from ALB security group


Click Create Service.
6. Access the Application
Once the service reaches Running status, open the ALB DNS:
http://<your-alb-dns>

Your application will load successfully.



