Create EKS cluster and deploy kubernetes in EKS

1. Steps to install AWS CLI and connect to AWS
1.1 curl "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-x86_64.zip" -o "awscliv2.zip"
Explanation:
 Downloads the AWS CLI v2 installer as a ZIP file to your current directory.
1.2 unzip awscliv2.zip
Explanation:
 Extracts the downloaded installer so you can run the setup script.
1.3 sudo ./aws/install
Explanation:
 	Runs the AWS CLI installer and installs the aws command globally on your system.
1.4 aws --version
Explanation:
 	Verifies that AWS CLI is installed correctly and shows the installed version.
1.5 aws configure
Explanation:
	 Starts an interactive setup to configure your AWS credentials and default region.
1.6 AWS Access Key ID: "enter your access key"
Explanation:
	 Enter the Access Key from your IAM user so the CLI can authenticate with AWS.
1.7 AWS Secret Access Key: "enter your secret key"
Explanation:
	 Enter the Secret Key that pairs with your Access Key. Keep this private.
1.8 Default region name: "ap-south-1"
Explanation:
 Sets ap-south-1 (Mumbai) as your default AWS region so all commands target this region automatically.

2. Steps to install kubectl
2.1 curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"
Explanation:
 	Downloads the latest stable kubectl binary for Linux (amd64 architecture).
2.2 chmod +x kubectl
Explanation:
 	Makes the kubectl file executable so it can be run as a command.
2.3 sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/kubectl
Explanation:
 	Moves kubectl into /usr/local/bin so it is available in your PATH globally.
2.4 kubectl version --client
Explanation:
 	Confirms that kubectl is installed and shows the client version.

3. Steps to install eksctl
3.1 curl -sLO "https://github.com/eksctl-io/eksctl/releases/latest/download/eksctl_$(uname -s)_amd64.tar.gz"
Explanation:
 Downloads the latest eksctl binary tarball for your OS (Linux) and amd64 architecture.

3.2 tar -xzf eksctl_$(uname -s)_amd64.tar.gz
Explanation:
 	Extracts the eksctl binary from the downloaded tar.gz archive.
3.3 sudo mv eksctl /usr/local/bin/
Explanation:
 Moves eksctl to /usr/local/bin so it can be used from anywhere in the terminal.
3.4 eksctl version
Explanation:
 	Checks that eksctl is installed successfully and prints the version.
4. Create EKS cluster
4.1
eksctl create cluster \
 	 --name zomato-eks-cluster \
 	 --region ap-south-1 \
  	--nodegroup-name ng-1 \
  	--node-type t3.medium \
  	--nodes 2 \
  	--nodes-min 2 \
  	--nodes-max 3 \
  	--managed
Explanation:
 Creates an EKS cluster named zomato-eks-cluster in region ap-south-1 with a managed node group:
2 worker nodes of type t3.medium


eksctl automatically creates VPC, subnets, security groups, IAM roles, etc.


This step may take several minutes to complete.

5. Configure kubectl to talk to EKS
5.1 aws eks update-kubeconfig --name zomato-eks-cluster --region ap-south-1
Explanation:
 Updates your local kubeconfig file so that kubectl knows how to connect to your new EKS cluster.
5.2 kubectl get nodes
Explanation:
 Lists the worker nodes in your EKS cluster. You should see 2 nodes in Ready status  if everything is correct.

6. Copy image URL from ECR
6.1 Go to AWS Console → ECR (Elastic Container Registry) → Repositories.
Explanation:
 ECR stores your Docker images. You must use the ECR image URL in your Kubernetes deployment.
6.2 Click on your repository, e.g., zomato-image (or whatever name you used).
Explanation:
 	Opens the repo that contains your zomato Docker image.
6.3 Copy the full image URI (example):
643625512213.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/zomato-image:latest
Explanation:
 This is the exact image URL that Kubernetes will pull from ECR when starting your pods. We will paste this into the deployment.yaml file.

7. Write Kubernetes YAML files
Create a folder to keep your Kubernetes manifests organized.
7.1 mkdir kubernetes
Explanation:
 	Creates a new directory named kubernetes to store your YAML files.
7.2 cd kubernetes
Explanation:
 	Moves into the kubernetes folder so you can create files inside it.
7.3 Create deployment.yaml
7.3.1
vi deployment.yaml

 Paste the following content (replace <paste copied image url> with your actual ECR image URI):

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  	name: zomato
  	labels:
    	app: zomato
spec:
  	replicas: 2
  	selector:
    	matchLabels:
      	app: zomato
  	template:
    	metadata:
      	labels:
        	app: zomato
    	spec:
      	containers:
      	- name: zomato
        	image: <paste copied image url>
        	ports:
        	- containerPort: 3000
Explanation:
Creates a Deployment named zomato


Runs 2 replicas (pods) of your app


Uses the ECR image you copied


Exposes container port 3000 inside the pod (your app should listen on this port)


After pasting, save and exit (Esc, then type :wq and press Enter).
7.4 Create service.yaml
7.4.1
vi service.yaml

 	Paste the following content:
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  	name: zomato
  	labels:
    	app: zomato
spec:
  	type: LoadBalancer
  	ports:
  	- port: 80
    	targetPort: 3000
  	selector:
    	app: zomato
Explanation:
Creates a Service named zomato


type: LoadBalancer tells AWS to create an external load balancer


The service listens on port 80 (public) and forwards traffic to port 3000 inside the pods


The selector finds all pods with label app: zomato (from your Deployment)


Save and exit (Esc, then :wq + Enter).
8. Deploy Kubernetes manifests into EKS
8.1 kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
Explanation:
 Creates the zomato Deployment in the EKS cluster and starts creating pods using your ECR image.
8.2 kubectl apply -f service.yaml
Explanation:
 Creates the zomato Service which exposes your pods through an AWS Load Balancer.
9. Verify pods and service
9.1 kubectl get pods

Explanation:
 Shows the status of all pods. They should move to Running state once the image is pulled successfully.
9.2 kubectl get svc
Explanation:
Lists all services. For the zomato service, you will see an EXTERNAL-IP assigned by AWS after a short time.
10. Test the application
10.1 Copy the EXTERNAL-IP or DNS name from the kubectl get svc output, for example:
a1b2c3d4e5f6-1234567890.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com
Explanation:
 This is the public URL of your load balancer that forwards traffic to your Kubernetes service.
10.2 curl http://a1b2c3d4e5f6-1234567890.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com
Explanation:
Sends an HTTP request to your application running inside EKS. You can also open this URL in a browser to see the UI if it’s a web app.
11. Clean up resources
11.1
kubectl delete -f service.yaml
kubectl delete -f deployment.yaml
Explanation:
	 Deletes the Kubernetes service and deployment so they stop running in the cluster.
11.2 eksctl delete cluster --name zomato-eks-cluster --region ap-south-1
Explanation:
 Completely removes your EKS cluster and all its associated resources (nodes, control plane, networking) to avoid extra AWS charges.
